-- Oil Rises on Improved U.S. Economic Data: Commodities at Close
-- B y   D a n i e l   E n o c h
-- 2011-12-22T21:59:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-22/oil-rises-on-improved-u-s-economic-data-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities rose 0.6 percent to close at 645.03 at 3:44 p.m.
in  New York , led by livestock, lead and aluminum. The UBS
Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials climbed 0.5 percent to
1,516.5.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil rose a fourth day as applications for
 unemployment benefits  in the U.S. decreased to a three-year low
and the index of U.S. leading indicators signaled that economic
growth will accelerate.  Oil for February delivery rose 86 cents to $99.53 a barrel
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the highest settlement
since Dec. 13. The intraday high was $100.05. Prices have
increased 10 percent this year after climbing 15 percent in
2010.  Brent-oil futures for February gained 18 cents to settle at
$107.89 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures  Europe 
exchange.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc purchased a North Sea Forties crude
cargo at a higher premium to Dated Brent. OAO Lukoil sold
Russian Urals blend in northwest Europe at a lower price.  Middle East crude for sale to  Asia  halted a three-day
decline against benchmark prices as processing profits for
refiners rose.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline futures rose after the U.S. said the number of
unemployment claims unexpectedly dropped last week, signaling a
strengthening economy.  Gasoline futures for January delivery rose 0.8 percent to
settle at $2.6398 a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
The futures are up 7.6 percent this year after gaining 20
percent last year and doubling in 2009.  Heating-oil futures for January delivery were little
changed, down 0.11 cent at $2.9076 a gallon on the Nymex.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas rose for the third straight day in New York as
traders took profits amid forecasts for mild weather that
threatens to send prices lower.  Gas futures for January delivery gained 1.4 cents to settle
at $3.169 per million British thermal units on the Nymex. The
commodity closed at a 27-month low of $3.096 on Dec. 19.  U.K. natural gas advanced amid thin trading as Britain
increased exports to  Belgium .  Gas for January delivery gained 0.2 percent to 56.05 pence
a therm in London, according to broker prices compiled by
Bloomberg. It was at 56.2 pence at 4:46 p.m. London time. That’s
equal to $8.80 per Btu. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Soybeans capped the longest rally since July and corn rose
to a one-month high on speculation that hot, dry weather is
hurting crops in  South America . Wheat also gained.  Soybean futures for March delivery advanced 0.7 percent to
close at $11.7175 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade, the
sixth straight gain. The price earlier touched $11.775, the
highest since Nov. 18.  Corn futures for March delivery climbed 0.2 percent to
$6.175 a bushel on the CBOT, capping the first five-session gain
since mid-May. Earlier, the most-active contract jumped as much
as 1.4 percent to $6.25, the highest since Nov. 18.  Wheat futures for March delivery rose 0.8 percent to
$6.2175 a bushel, after gaining 6.5 percent in the previous four
sessions. The grain has fallen 22 percent this year on rising
world production and slowing demand for U.S. supplies.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold declined in New York for the third time in four days
on signs of a strengthening U.S. job market and a drop in
holdings by exchange-traded fund investors.  Gold futures for February delivery dropped 0.2 percent to
settle at $1,610.60 an ounce on the Comex in New York. The metal
has climbed 13 percent this year. Prices dropped 6.9 percent
last week after the  Federal Reserve  refrained from taking new
action to boost economic growth.  Silver futures for March delivery fell 0.7 percent to
$29.047 an ounce on the Comex, extending this year’s decline to
6.1 percent.  On the Nymex, palladium futures for March delivery jumped
3.2 percent, the most since Dec. 6, to $654.40 an ounce.
Platinum futures for January delivery fell 0.5 percent to
$1,431.20 an ounce.  BASE METALS  Copper climbed for a third day, the longest rally this
month, as U.S. reports showed an improved labor outlook and
gains in  consumer confidence , boosting demand prospects for the
metal used in pipes and wires.  Copper futures for March delivery rose 0.6 percent to
$3.4155 a pound on the Comex. The price gained 2.6 percent in
the previous two sessions as Chinese imports of the industrial
metal climbed to the highest since June 2009.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months rose 1.1 percent to $7,540 a metric ton ($3.42 a pound).
Tin, aluminum and lead also climbed in London. Nickel and
zinc fell.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cocoa fell for the first time in three days on signs that a
disagreement over port fees that hampered exports is close to
being resolved in  Ghana , the world’s second-biggest grower.  Cocoa for March delivery fell 1 percent to settle at $2,221
a metric ton on ICE Futures U.S. in New York. Prices have
dropped 27 percent this year.  Arabica-coffee futures for March delivery gained 0.7
percent to $2.214 a pound in New York, the third gain in four
days. The commodity has dropped 7.9 percent in 2011.  Raw-sugar futures for March delivery rose 0.5 percent to
23.44 cents a pound on ICE. The sweetener has fallen 27 percent
this year.  Cotton futures for March delivery rose 0.5 percent to
settle at 87.24 cents a pound on ICE. The price has plunged 40
percent this year and is on pace for the biggest annual decline
since 2004.  Orange-juice futures for March delivery added 0.5 percent
to $1.64 a pound in New York. The price is up 0.3 percent this
year.  In London futures trading, cocoa and robusta coffee fell,
while refined sugar gained.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle climbed to the highest in almost three weeks on
speculation that a winter storm in one of the biggest U.S. beef-
producing regions has reduced the availability of meat.  Cattle futures for February delivery rose 3 cents, the
maximum allowed by the  Chicago  Mercantile Exchange, capping a
2.5 percent gain to settle at $1.2345 a pound. That’s the
highest for the most active contract since Dec. 2, and prices
are up 14 percent this year.  Feeder-cattle futures for March settlement increased 1.9
percent to $1.4965 a pound on the CME, after reaching $1.497,
the highest for a most-active contract since Nov. 18.  Hog futures for February settlement advanced 1.5 percent to
settle at 84.55 cents a pound in Chicago. The price has risen 6
percent in 2011.  To contact the reporter on this story:
